The easiest way to do this is to use a very common testing pattern. It&#39;s well described in JB Rainsberger&#39;s JUnit 
Recipes book (which everyone on this mailing list ends up recommending once every few months or so), but essentially you 
create a test fixture and then use the Template Method pattern to create your implementation. A test suite might be a 
good idea to package all of the different implementation test classes together.

In JUnit 3.8.2 code (it&#39;d be nicer in JUnit 4):

public abstract class AlgorithmTestCase extends TestCase {
   private Algorithm m_algorithm;
   public void testCalculate() {
     // do your test on m_algorithm
   }

   protected void setUp() {
     m_algorithm = makeAlgorithm();
   }

   protected void tearDown() {
     m_algorithm = null;
   }

   protected abstract Algorithm makeAlgorithm();
}

public class Algorithm1Test extends AlgorithmTestCase {
   protected Algorithm makeAlgorithm() {
     return new Algorithm1();
   }
}

